{
  "text": "Monocyte/macrophage-derived NO may also block replication of DENV, another mosquito-transmitted flavivirus. Infection with DENV resulted in increased levels of NO in patients with dengue fever, the classic form of the disease [CITATION_1] . Additionally, iNOS expression was induced in CD14 + monocytes from a subset of acutely infected individuals [CITATION_2] . It was further shown that ex vivo infection of human monocytes with DENV-1 resulted in increased iNOS expression, and inhibition of iNOS activity led to increased DENV antigen detection in these cells [CITATION_3] . Moreover, treatment of C6/36 mosquito cells with an NO donor resulted in reduced DENV-positive cells [CITATION_4] . These data suggest that DENV replication is susceptible to NO-mediated inhibition. Consistent with this, Nos2 \u2212/\u2212 mice were shown to be more susceptible to DENV infection, resulting in more severe disease and increased lethality in mouse models of DENV-2 and DENV-3 infection [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . It was further demonstrated that, following DENV infection in vivo, IL-12 and IL-18 induced IFN-\u03b3 production, resulting in iNOS expression and NO production, which contributed to viral control [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
